      <h2>Commercial Stove Types and Their Repair Needs</h2>
      <p><strong>Gas Stoves:</strong></p>
      <p>Gas stoves are a popular choice in many commercial kitchens due to their quick heating and precise temperature
        control. However, they come with their own set of repair needs. Common issues include malfunctioning burners, gas
        leaks, and problems with the ignition system. Repairing a gas stove often involves checking the gas lines for leaks,
        cleaning or replacing clogged burners, and fixing or replacing the ignition switch. Costs for these repairs can vary,
        but typically range from $150 to $400, depending on the severity of the issue. Regular maintenance, such as cleaning
        burners and checking gas connections, can help prevent many of these problems and ensure the stove operates
        efficiently.</p>
      <p><strong>Electric Stoves:</strong></p>
      <p>Electric stoves are known for their even heating and ease of use, making them another popular option in commercial
        settings. Common issues with electric stoves include faulty heating elements, broken thermostats, and issues with the
        stove’s wiring. Repairs might involve replacing a heating element, fixing wiring issues, or recalibrating the
        thermostat. These repairs generally cost between $100 and $300. Regular maintenance for electric stoves includes
        checking the heating elements for wear and ensuring that the electrical connections are secure. By addressing minor
        issues early on, businesses can avoid more costly repairs and prolong the life of their electric stoves.</p>
      <p><strong>Induction Stoves:</strong></p>
      <p>Induction stoves are highly efficient and provide rapid heating by using electromagnetic fields to directly heat
        cookware. However, they require specialized repairs when issues arise. Common problems include malfunctioning
        induction coils, faulty control panels, and issues with the stove's sensors. Repairing an induction stove can be more
        complex and may require specialized knowledge, often leading to higher repair costs ranging from $200 to $500. Regular
        maintenance, such as cleaning the cooktop surface and ensuring that the cookware used is compatible with induction
        cooking, can help prevent many common issues and keep the stove in optimal working condition.</p>
      <p><strong>Dual Fuel Stoves:</strong></p>
      <p>Dual fuel stoves combine the best of both gas and electric stoves, offering a gas cooktop with an electric oven.
        While they provide versatility and precision, they also come with a unique set of repair needs. Issues can arise in
        both the gas and electric components, including problems with gas burners, electric heating elements, and electronic
        control systems. Repairing a dual fuel stove can be more involved and costly, with prices typically ranging from $250
        to $600, depending on the nature of the problem. Regular maintenance should include checking both gas and electric
        components, cleaning burners, and ensuring that the control systems are functioning correctly. This holistic approach
        to maintenance can help prevent costly breakdowns and extend the life of the stove.</p>
      <p><strong>Convection Stoves:</strong></p>
      <p>Convection stoves are prized for their ability to cook food evenly and quickly, thanks to a built-in fan that
        circulates hot air. Common repair needs for convection stoves include issues with the convection fan, heating
