      <p><strong>Burner Malfunctions:</strong></p>
      <p>Burner malfunctions are a frequent issue in commercial stoves, significantly impacting kitchen efficiency. Common
        symptoms include burners that won’t ignite, uneven flame distribution, or burners that don't heat up at all. The root
        causes can vary from clogged ports and faulty igniters to broken gas lines or electrical issues. Resolving burner
        malfunctions typically involves cleaning the burner components, replacing defective igniters, or repairing gas or
        electrical connections. Regular cleaning and inspection can help prevent these issues, but when they do occur,
        professional repair services are often required to ensure safety and proper functionality. Costs for these repairs can
        range from $100 to $300, depending on the complexity of the problem.</p>
      <p><strong>Oven Temperature Inconsistencies:</strong></p>
      <p>Temperature inconsistencies in the oven can lead to uneven cooking, affecting food quality and customer satisfaction.
        Common causes include faulty thermostats, malfunctioning temperature sensors, or issues with the heating elements.
        Repairing these issues may involve recalibrating or replacing the thermostat, testing and replacing temperature
        sensors, or repairing the heating elements. The cost for these repairs generally falls between $150 and $400. Regular
        oven calibration and maintenance can help detect early signs of temperature problems, ensuring that the oven maintains
        the correct temperature and cooks food evenly.</p>
      <p><strong>Ignition Problems:</strong></p>
      <p>Ignition problems are another prevalent issue, particularly in gas stoves. Symptoms include a clicking sound without
        ignition, delayed ignition, or no ignition at all. These problems can be caused by dirty or clogged igniters, faulty
        ignition switches, or issues with the gas supply. Repairing ignition problems usually involves cleaning the igniters,
        replacing defective parts, or checking and adjusting the gas supply. The cost for these repairs can range from $100 to
        $250. Routine cleaning and inspection of the ignition components can help prevent these issues and ensure reliable
        stove performance.</p>
      <p><strong>Gas Leaks:</strong></p>
      <p>Gas leaks are a serious issue that requires immediate attention due to the potential safety hazards, including fire
        and explosion risks. Common indicators of a gas leak include the smell of gas, hissing sounds, or a visible drop in
        gas pressure. Causes can include damaged gas lines, loose connections, or faulty valves. Repairing gas leaks involves
        identifying the leak source, repairing or replacing damaged components, and ensuring all connections are secure. The
        cost for these repairs can be higher, typically ranging from $200 to $500, due to the urgency and safety precautions
        involved. Regular inspection of gas lines and connections can help detect and address leaks before they become
        dangerous.</p>
      <p><strong>Control Panel Failures:</strong></p>
      <p>Control panel failures can disrupt the entire cooking process, as the control panel is responsible for managing the
        stove's functions. Symptoms include unresponsive buttons, error messages, or the stove not turning on. Common causes
        include electrical issues, faulty wiring, or damaged control boards. Repairing control panel failures often involves
        diagnosing electrical problems, repairing or replacing the wiring, or installing a new control board. Costs for these
        repairs can range from $200 to $600, depending on the extent of the damage. Regular maintenance and prompt attention
        to minor electrical issues can help prevent control panel failures and ensure the stove remains fully operational.</p>
      <p><strong>Ventilation Issues:</strong></p>
      <p>Proper ventilation is critical in commercial kitchens to maintain air quality and ensure the safe operation of
        stoves. Common ventilation issues include clogged filters, malfunctioning exhaust fans, or blocked ductwork. Symptoms
        can include poor air circulation, excessive smoke, or lingering cooking odors. Repairing ventilation issues may
        involve cleaning or replacing filters, repairing or replacing exhaust fans, or clearing blockages in the ductwork.
